1
00:00:00,080 --> 00:00:20,960
All right, Crawl here again for our final chapter. Insurance is a promise and promises require trust. To even buy a policy, you must have an insurable interest. This means you legally own or have a stake in the car, and you would suffer a true financial loss if it were destroyed.

2
00:00:20,960 --> 00:00:53,680
You must also practice utmost good faith. You are required to fully and honestly disclose how you use the vehicle. If you hide the truth, the promise is broken. When a crash happens, the principle of proximate cause dictates that the insurer only pays if a covered peril was the direct active cause of the damage. And through the principle of indemnity, the payout is designed to put you back in the exact financial position you were in right before the accident. No better, no worse.

3
00:00:53,680 --> 00:01:12,400
If you have multiple policies covering the same car, the principle of contribution ensures the companies share the claim. And if another reckless driver hits you, the principle of subrogation allows your insurer to pay your claim immediately, then take over your legal right to pursue the at-fault driver for the money.

4
00:01:12,400 --> 00:01:31,360
There are also hard boundaries. You are not protected if you drive outside the Philippines, use the car for racing, or haul highly inflammable materials. Standard policies also will not cover acts of nature like floods or earthquakes unless you specifically add that coverage.

5
00:01:31,360 --> 00:02:04,399
Finally, know your rights. You can cancel your policy anytime, though a short period rate scale penalty applies to cover administrative costs. If you and the insurer disagree on a claim amount, arbitration is required before any lawsuits can be filed. Ultimately, your greatest duty is to safeguard your vehicle and drive carefully. Protect yourself, protect others, and respect the road. Thank you for learning with me.